{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4da1f9c2-dd1b-4d78-b573-e3aebb9ff6b6","content":"You can download `dotnet-trace` as a **standalone tool** — no SDK needed. Inside your container, run:\n\n```bash\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o /tmp/dotnet-trace\nchmod +x /tmp/dotnet-trace\n```\n\nThen collect a CPU trace:\n\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n/tmp/dotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU profiling trace\n/tmp/dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**Key notes:**\n- Use `linux-arm64` instead of `linux-x64` if you're on ARM.\n- The output `.nettrace` file can be analyzed with **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or converted to Speedscope format with `--format speedscope`.\n- If the container lacks `curl`, you can `docker cp` the binary in from the host.\n- Ensure the tool and app target compatible .NET versions (the .NET 8 standalone build works for .NET 8 apps).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0efc567d-f361-452e-9765-72f21b282b02","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed, to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app experiencing high CPU.\n\nThis is a knowledge question about .NET diagnostics tooling. I can answer this directly from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase.\n\nKey points:\n1. `dotnet-trace` is a .NET global tool, but you can also get it as a standalone download (no SDK required).\n2. For containers without the SDK, you can download the standalone version.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":415,"requestId":"67CB:1EAD:490195B:4FC58B2:69FD3C92"},"id":"d93a3943-b728-4228-ae59-07e83acfda47","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:30:08.666Z","parentId":"68d99c18-e4a1-442d-8cf6-03796bc18fa6"}
